Univariate Analysis

In [ ]:
# Age is concentrated between 25–40 years.
# Salary distribution appears right-skewed.
for num_var in ["Age", "No_of_Dependents", "Salary", "Partner_salary", "Total_salary", "Price"]:
     plt.figure()
     sns.histplot(x=num_var, data=df,kde=True)
     plt.title(f'countof {num_var}')
     plt.xticks(rotation=45)
     plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Hatchbacks have highest frequency.
# Majority customers are salaried.
# Most of them have personal loans.

for cat_var in ["Gender","Marital_status","Education","Profession","Make","Personal_loan","House_loan","Partner_working"]:
  if cat_var in df.columns:
    plt.figure()
    sns.countplot(x=cat_var, data=df)
    plt.title(f'count of {cat_var}')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()

In [ ]:
# sns.barplot give us the exact model/make
# SUVs have the highest average price, followed by Sedans and Hatchbacks
sns.barplot(x="Make", y="Price", data=df)
plt.title("Make vs Price")
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Make vs Price')
In [ ]:
# Analyzing whether age is influncing car choices.
# SUV buyers appear slightly older on average, this give us info that age is infulincing the car Make.
sns.barplot(x='Make', y='Age', data=df)
plt.title("Age Vs Make Barplot")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Comparing average price across car segments
# Comparatively from the boxplot we can see that people are moving from Hatchback to SUV as the salary goes up.
for num_var in ["Price", "Total_salary", "Salary", "Partner_salary"]:
    plt.Figure()
    sns.boxplot(x=df['Make'],y=num_var,data=df)
    plt.title(f'{num_var} by Price outcome')
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Checking relationship between age and car price
# From the scatter plot we can see that there is strong correlation between age and price.
sns.scatterplot(x="Age", y="Price", hue="Make", data=df,alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Price vs Age scatterplot")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# From the scatterplot we can see that there is relationship between total_salary and price, which indicate that affordability plays a major role in car selection.
sns.scatterplot(x="Total_salary", y="Price",hue="Make", data=df, alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Price vs Total_salary scatterplot")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# From the heatmap we can see that Total_Salary shows strong correlation than with the single salary.
df_corr= df.corr(numeric_only=True)
sns.heatmap(df_corr,annot=True)
plt.show()

Insights



Young professionals dominate market

Hatchbacks has the high volume

SUVs target high-income households

Household (Total_salary) income strongly impact car price

Clear opportunity for segmented marketing
